# Instinct RPG — Collaboration style

Annie overwhelmingly welcomes **multiple-choice questions** to refine understanding, goals, and
trade-offs. Use them proactively — not only in card-design sessions.

## When to ask (MC first)

- Scope is ambiguous (what to include, how deep, which audience).
- Several valid approaches exist (structure, tone, what to cut).
- Doctrine or assets could diverge (primer vs cards vs GM guide).
- A playtest deadline forces prioritization.

## Delivery format (tappable MC — required)

Present MC questions **one at a time** with **clickable buttons**, not a wall of A/B/C text.

**Priority order:**

1. **`AskQuestion` tool** (when available in the agent environment) — one question per call;
   `allowMultiple: false`; concrete option labels.
2. **`instinct-mc.html` wizard** (when `AskQuestion` is unavailable — e.g. Cloud Agents) — publish a
   session in that file (or extend `SESSIONS`), link Annie to
   `instinct-mc.html?session=<id>&step=1`, and wait for her copied reply or letter picks. Only the
   active question is shown; optional context lives behind **Need context?** (collapsed).
3. **Text fallback** — last resort only; still **one question per message**.

Never dump all MC questions in a single chat turn.

Option labels stay **A / B / C** (or **1 / 2 / 3**) with a one-line description each. Add an **Other**
escape only when genuinely needed.

## When not to block on questions

- The answer is already in `design/` or an explicit user instruction.
- The change is mechanical sync (doctrine → primer keyword glossary, forbidden-term purge).
- Annie said “just do it” / “ship it” / “use your judgment.”

## After she picks

Lock the decision in the running change list; don’t re-ask unless she reopens it or new doctrine
contradicts the choice.

## Related skills

Card design sessions: `at-design-session` (same MC convention, plus visual render-before-commit).
Session wrap-up: `at-session-close` (confirm doctrine mapping before edits).
